Give Me The Code

Technical details	
Submit file	./src/main/java/*.java, pom.xml or build.gradle, README.md, etc.
Give me the .... LeetCode API
Objective
Build a RESTful web service using Spring Boot that consumes the LeetCode API to fetch daily coding challenges. Implement Spring Security with JWT for authentication and authorization, and use HATEOAS for hypermedia-driven interactions. Store user challenge history, including attempted challenges, number of successful attempts, and failed attempts.

Requirements
1. Project Structure
Organize your project with the following structure

daily-coding-challenges/
|-- src/
|   |-- main/
|   |   |-- java/
|   |   |   |-- com/
|   |   |       |-- example/
|   |   |           |-- controller/
|   |   |           |-- model/
|   |   |           |-- service/
|   |   |           |-- security/
|   |   |           |-- repository/
|   |   |           |-- config/
|   |   |-- resources/
|   |       |-- application.properties
|-- pom.xml
2. Implementations
A. Model Layer
Define the data models for challenges and user history.
Example Challenge.java

package com.example.model;

import javax.persistence.Entity;
import javax.persistence.GeneratedValue;
import javax.persistence.GenerationType;
import javax.persistence.Id;

@Entity
public class Challenge {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;
    private String title;
    private String difficulty;
}
Example UserHistory.java

package com.example.model;

import javax.persistence.Entity;
import javax.persistence.GeneratedValue;
import javax.persistence.GenerationType;
import javax.persistence.Id;

@Entity
public class UserHistory {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;
    private Long userId;
    private Long challengeId;
    private boolean success;
}
B. Repository Layer
Create repositories to manage database interactions.
Example ChallengeRepository.java

package com.example.repository;

import com.example.model.Challenge;
import org.springframework.data.jpa.repository.JpaRepository;

public interface ChallengeRepository extends JpaRepository<Challenge, Long> {
}
Example UserHistoryRepository.java

package com.example.repository;

import com.example.model.UserHistory;
import org.springframework.data.jpa.repository.JpaRepository;

import java.util.List;

public interface UserHistoryRepository extends JpaRepository<UserHistory, Long> {
    List<UserHistory> findByUserId(Long userId);
}
C. Service Layer
Create a service class to handle business logic.
Example ChallengeService.java

package com.example.service;

import com.example.model.Challenge;
import com.example.repository.ChallengeRepository;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

import java.util.List;

@Service
public class ChallengeService {
    private final ChallengeRepository challengeRepository;

    public ChallengeService(ChallengeRepository challengeRepository) {
        this.challengeRepository = challengeRepository;
    }

    public List<Challenge> getDailyChallenges() {
        return challengeRepository.findAll(); // This would be replaced with API fetching
    }
}
D. Security Layer
Implement JWT-based authentication.
E. Controller Layer
Create REST controllers to handle incoming requests.
Example ChallengeController.java

3. Configuration
Set up your application properties for database connection and JWT secret.
4. Running the Application
Package the application using Maven.

Run the application using ./mvnw spring-boot:run.

Use a tool like Postman to test the REST APIs, ensuring you obtain a JWT token for authentication.

5. Evaluation Criteria:
Proper implementation of RESTful services.

Effective use of Spring Security and JWT.

HATEOAS principles applied in API responses.

Comprehensive user history tracking.

Code quality, adherence to best practices, and proper documentation.

